cally provocative, the volume introduces readers to cutting-edge temporal conceptualizations and investigates what exactly constitutes the scope of time studies.Featuring twenty essays that reveal what we talk about when we talk about time today, especially in the areas of history, measurement, and culture, each essay pairs two keywords to explore the tension and nuances between them, from “past/future” and “anticipation/unexpected” to “extinction/adaptation” and “serial/simultaneous.” Moving beyond the truisms of postmodernism, the collection newly theorizes the meanings of temporality in relationship to aesthetic, cultural, technological, and economic developments in the postwar period. This book thus assumes that time—not space, as the postmoderns had it—is central to the contemporary period, and that through it we can come to terms with what contemporaneity can be for human beings caught up in the historical present. In the end, Time reveals that the present is a cultural matrix in which overlapping temporalities condition and compete for our attention. Thus each pair of terms presents two temporalities, yielding a generative account of the time, or times, in which we live.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aHorology. 0aTimexPhilosophy. 0aTimexPsychological aspects. 0aTime. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Criticism.2bisacsh1 aAnable, Aubrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnderson, Ben, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurges, Joel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurges, Joel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCanales, Jimena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCurrie, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElias, Amy J.,